<h2 id="overview">1. Overview</h2>

<p>
This document defines the <strong>FROG Snippet</strong> model used by a FROG IDE for reusable partial program artifacts.
A FROG Snippet is an IDE-level artifact intended for copy/paste, drag-and-drop, sharing, and reuse of source-aligned fragments.
</p>

<p>
A FROG Snippet is <strong>not</strong> the canonical source representation of a full program.
The canonical source representation of a full program remains the <code>.frog</code> file defined by the FROG Expression layer.
</p>

<p>
A snippet captures a reusable fragment of authoring state, typically including:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>a selected diagram fragment,</li>
  <li>an optional related front-panel fragment,</li>
  <li>local layout and editor-facing information needed for reuse,</li>
  <li>boundary information for connections cut by the selection,</li>
  <li>optional preview data.</li>
</ul>

<p>
The purpose of a snippet is to make reuse fast and tool-friendly without collapsing the language into a closed editor-specific format.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="goals">2. Goals</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Reuse</strong> — allow users to capture and reinsert useful diagram and UI fragments quickly.</li>
  <li><strong>Portability</strong> — allow snippet exchange across FROG-compatible IDEs without requiring a full project export.</li>
  <li><strong>Source alignment</strong> — keep snippet content expressible in terms of source-level FROG objects.</li>
  <li><strong>Structural safety</strong> — ensure that snippets preserve valid ownership, scope, and fragment boundaries.</li>
  <li><strong>Extensibility</strong> — allow richer previews, metadata, and packaging later without changing the base semantic model.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="scope-for-v01">3. Scope for v0.1</h2>

<p>
For FROG v0.1, this document standardizes:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>the concept of a FROG Snippet,</li>
  <li>the distinction between snippet artifacts and canonical program source,</li>
  <li>the minimal top-level snippet structure,</li>
  <li>diagram-fragment snippets,</li>
  <li>front-panel-fragment snippets,</li>
  <li>paired diagram + front-panel snippets,</li>
  <li>selection-closure and boundary rules,</li>
  <li>basic export and import semantics.</li>
</ul>

<p>
FROG v0.1 does <strong>not</strong> standardize:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>a mandatory clipboard protocol,</li>
  <li>a mandatory drag-and-drop protocol,</li>
  <li>a mandatory repository packaging format for snippet libraries,</li>
  <li>marketplace-style snippet distribution,</li>
  <li>signed snippet packages,</li>
  <li>live executable snippet previews,</li>
  <li>automatic semantic adaptation of snippets across incompatible profiles.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="relation-with-other-specifications">4. Relation with Other Specifications</h2>

<p>
This document complements the following specifications:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>IDE/Readme.md</code> — defines the role of the IDE, the Program Model, and source-aligned editing responsibilities.</li>
  <li><code>IDE/Palette.md</code> — defines how reusable authoring elements may be surfaced within the IDE.</li>
  <li><code>Expression/Diagram.md</code> — defines the executable graph, source-level node kinds, ports, and edges.</li>
  <li><code>Expression/Front panel.md</code> — defines front-panel widget composition and UI structure.</li>
  <li><code>Expression/Widget.md</code> — defines the widget object model and widget identity rules.</li>
</ul>

<p>
A FROG Snippet is an IDE artifact derived from Program Model content and source-level concepts.
It does not replace the full FROG Expression and does not redefine the serialized structure of a complete <code>.frog</code> file.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="design-principles">5. Design Principles</h2>

<h3>5.1 Snippet is not full source</h3>

<p>
A FROG Snippet MUST be treated as a partial reusable artifact.
It MUST NOT be treated as a complete canonical program source unless it independently satisfies the rules of a full FROG Expression, which is outside the purpose of this document.
</p>

<h3>5.2 Source-level structure first</h3>

<p>
Snippet content MUST be expressible in terms of source-level objects such as nodes, edges, widget subtrees, regions, and editor-facing fragment metadata.
It MUST NOT depend on runtime-private representations.
</p>

<h3>5.3 Structural closure</h3>

<p>
A snippet MUST preserve ownership and scope boundaries.
Selections that cut across ownership in invalid ways MUST be rejected or normalized before export.
</p>

<h3>5.4 Non-authoritative preview</h3>

<p>
A snippet MAY contain preview information such as a thumbnail or lightweight display metadata.
Such preview information is non-authoritative and MUST NOT redefine snippet semantics.
</p>

<h3>5.5 Import safety</h3>

<p>
Importing a snippet MUST preserve source-level validity rules of the target Program Model.
Identifiers, ownership, and boundary connections MUST be normalized during import.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="what-a-frog-snippet-is">6. What a FROG Snippet Is</h2>

<p>
A FROG Snippet is a reusable IDE artifact representing a selected source-aligned fragment.
It is typically created from an IDE selection and later inserted into another location through paste, drag-and-drop, or snippet import.
</p>

<p>
A snippet may represent:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>a diagram-only fragment,</li>
  <li>a front-panel-only fragment,</li>
  <li>a paired fragment that includes both diagram and front-panel content.</li>
</ul>

<p>
A snippet may also contain boundary descriptors for connections or references that were cut by the selection.
This allows an IDE to preserve fragment meaning without pretending that the fragment is already a complete stand-alone program.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="snippet-kinds">7. Snippet Kinds</h2>

<p>
The canonical snippet kinds for FROG v0.1 are:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>diagram_snippet</code> — a diagram fragment only,</li>
  <li><code>front_panel_snippet</code> — a front-panel fragment only,</li>
  <li><code>paired_snippet</code> — a diagram fragment plus an associated front-panel fragment.</li>
</ul>

<p>
A FROG IDE SHOULD support <code>diagram_snippet</code> as the minimal required kind.
Support for <code>front_panel_snippet</code> and <code>paired_snippet</code> is strongly recommended.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="transport-forms">8. Transport Forms</h2>

<h3>8.1 General rule</h3>

<p>
A snippet is a conceptual artifact.
An implementation MAY transport it through:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>clipboard payloads,</li>
  <li>drag-and-drop payloads,</li>
  <li>standalone snippet files,</li>
  <li>project-local snippet libraries,</li>
  <li>other equivalent IDE-managed transport forms.</li>
</ul>

<h3>8.2 Standalone file form</h3>

<p>
For portable file-based exchange, FROG v0.1 defines the canonical standalone snippet extension:
</p>

<pre><code>.frogsnippet</code></pre>

<p>
The canonical snippet file payload is a structured text representation intended to be tool-readable and version-control-friendly.
A preview image MAY be stored alongside or embedded as non-authoritative auxiliary data.
</p>

<h3>8.3 No image-carrier requirement</h3>

<p>
FROG v0.1 does not require snippets to be encoded inside an image carrier.
A preview image MAY exist, but the canonical snippet meaning is defined by structured snippet data rather than by steganographic or image-only transport.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="top-level-model">9. Top-Level Model</h2>

<p>
The canonical top-level shape of a snippet artifact is conceptually:
</p>

<pre><code>{
  "kind": "frog_snippet",
  "version": "0.1",
  "snippet_kind": "diagram_snippet | front_panel_snippet | paired_snippet",
  "diagram_fragment": { ... },
  "front_panel_fragment": { ... },
  "boundaries": { ... },
  "dependencies": { ... },
  "preview": { ... },
  "metadata": { ... }
}</code></pre>

<p>
Rules:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>kind</code> MUST be <code>frog_snippet</code>,</li>
  <li><code>version</code> MUST identify the snippet-format version,</li>
  <li><code>snippet_kind</code> MUST identify the snippet category,</li>
  <li><code>diagram_fragment</code> MUST be present for <code>diagram_snippet</code> and <code>paired_snippet</code>,</li>
  <li><code>front_panel_fragment</code> MUST be present for <code>front_panel_snippet</code> and <code>paired_snippet</code>.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Auxiliary sections such as <code>preview</code>, <code>metadata</code>, and implementation-private editor hints MAY be present provided that they remain non-authoritative.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="diagram-fragment-model">10. Diagram Fragment Model</h2>

<p>
A diagram fragment represents a selected subset of one diagram scope.
It MUST be expressible using the same source-level concepts used by the FROG diagram model, including:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>selected nodes,</li>
  <li>selected edges between those nodes,</li>
  <li>annotations and local layout information,</li>
  <li>boundary descriptors for cut external connections.</li>
</ul>

<p>
A diagram fragment MUST belong to exactly one source diagram scope.
It MUST NOT mix content from multiple independent diagram scopes in one fragment unless a stricter profile defines a normalized representation for doing so.
</p>

<p>
The fragment MAY include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>primitive nodes,</li>
  <li>structure nodes,</li>
  <li>sub-FROG nodes,</li>
  <li>interface boundary nodes when meaningful in the local source context,</li>
  <li><code>widget_value</code> nodes,</li>
  <li><code>widget_reference</code> nodes,</li>
  <li>comments and documentation annotations,</li>
  <li>local geometry or editor layout hints.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="front-panel-fragment-model">11. Front Panel Fragment Model</h2>

<p>
A front-panel fragment represents one or more selected widget subtrees and their local layout and presentation information.
It MUST use source-level front-panel and widget concepts rather than editor-private rendered surfaces.
</p>

<p>
A front-panel fragment MAY include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>widget subtree roots,</li>
  <li>nested child widgets,</li>
  <li>layout and styling properties,</li>
  <li>non-authoritative editor hints for placement or grouping.</li>
</ul>

<p>
A front-panel fragment MUST preserve widget ownership correctly.
A snippet MUST NOT contain a cut partial widget object that omits required subtree structure.
</p>

<p>
For a <code>paired_snippet</code>, the front-panel fragment MAY be associated with diagram-side widget-related nodes contained in the paired diagram fragment.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="selection-closure-rules">12. Selection Closure Rules</h2>

<h3>12.1 Diagram-scope closure</h3>

<p>
A diagram snippet MUST be structurally closed with respect to diagram ownership.
A selection that cuts across incompatible ownership boundaries MUST be rejected or normalized before snippet export.
</p>

<h3>12.2 Region closure</h3>

<p>
If a selection includes content inside a structure-owned region, the selection MUST remain valid with respect to that region.
A snippet MUST NOT silently flatten or distort region ownership.
</p>

<p>
For v0.1:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>a snippet MAY contain content wholly inside one region,</li>
  <li>a snippet MAY contain a structure node together with its owned regions,</li>
  <li>a snippet MUST NOT export a semantically broken partial structure ownership graph.</li>
</ul>

<h3>12.3 Front-panel closure</h3>

<p>
A front-panel snippet MUST be closed with respect to widget ownership.
It MAY contain one or more complete widget subtrees.
It MUST NOT export an invalid partial widget subtree.
</p>

<h3>12.4 Mixed-scope rejection</h3>

<p>
If the user selection mixes incompatible source ownership scopes and the IDE cannot normalize them safely, snippet export MUST fail rather than producing a semantically misleading snippet.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="snippet-boundaries">13. Snippet Boundaries</h2>

<h3>13.1 Purpose</h3>

<p>
A snippet often cuts connections to objects that are outside the selection.
Those cut connections MUST be represented explicitly as snippet boundaries rather than being silently discarded.
</p>

<h3>13.2 Boundary descriptors</h3>

<p>
A snippet boundary descriptor conceptually identifies:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>an exposed incoming requirement into the snippet fragment,</li>
  <li>an exposed outgoing result from the snippet fragment,</li>
  <li>the local node and port involved,</li>
  <li>the expected type when known.</li>
</ul>

<h3>13.3 Meaning</h3>

<p>
Boundary descriptors do not turn the snippet into a full callable FROG.
They simply preserve the local fragment interface produced by selection cutting.
</p>

<p>
An IDE MAY visualize these boundaries as:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>dangling snippet ports,</li>
  <li>preview connectors,</li>
  <li>paste-time attachment handles.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="dependencies-and-references">14. Dependencies and References</h2>

<p>
A snippet MAY reference external dependencies required for correct reuse, such as:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>standard primitive namespaces,</li>
  <li>sub-FROG references,</li>
  <li>UI library references,</li>
  <li>type names or profile-related requirements.</li>
</ul>

<p>
For v0.1, dependency declarations SHOULD remain lightweight.
They are intended to help import validation and user feedback, not to define a full package-management system.
</p>

<p>
A snippet MUST NOT claim that referenced external dependencies are embedded unless they are actually included in the snippet artifact.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="preview-and-presentation">15. Preview and Presentation</h2>

<p>
A snippet MAY contain a non-authoritative preview used by IDEs for browsing, drag-and-drop, or gallery presentation.
Examples include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>a diagram thumbnail,</li>
  <li>a front-panel thumbnail,</li>
  <li>a compact label or title,</li>
  <li>a short description.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Preview data MUST remain non-authoritative.
The snippet’s semantic meaning is defined by its structured fragment content, not by its preview rendering.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="export-semantics">16. Export Semantics</h2>

<h3>16.1 General rule</h3>

<p>
Snippet export is performed from the current Program Model selection.
The export process MUST preserve source-level fragment meaning while normalizing the selection into a structurally valid snippet artifact.
</p>

<h3>16.2 Export responsibilities</h3>

<p>
An exporting IDE SHOULD:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>capture selected source-level objects,</li>
  <li>preserve internal connectivity within the selection,</li>
  <li>derive explicit boundary descriptors for cut external connections,</li>
  <li>capture enough local layout information for useful reinsertion,</li>
  <li>record minimal dependency information needed for later validation.</li>
</ul>

<h3>16.3 Identifier normalization</h3>

<p>
Snippet-local identifiers MAY be preserved for internal consistency within the snippet artifact.
However, they MUST NOT be assumed to remain globally unique when the snippet is imported into another Program Model.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2 id="import-semantics">17. Import Semantics</h2>

<h3>17.1 General rule</h3>

<p>
Snippet import inserts the snippet fragment into a target Program Model and target editing context.
The imported result MUST satisfy the same source-level validity rules that apply to ordinary edited content.
</p>

<h3>17.2 Identifier regeneration</h3>

<p>
When necessary, an importing IDE MUST regenerate identifiers so that imported snippet objects do not collide with existing Program Model identifiers.
</p>

<h3>17.3 Internal preservation</h3>

<p>
Import MUST preserve:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>the internal node set,</li>
  <li>the internal edge topology,</li>
  <li>owned regions and scopes,</li>
  <li>widget subtree ownership,</li>
  <li>source-level object relationships.</li>
</ul>

<h3>17.4 Boundary reconnection</h3>

<p>
Snippet boundaries MAY remain disconnected after import.
An IDE MAY help the user reconnect them, but such reconnection MUST be explicit or clearly user-directed.
Import MUST NOT silently invent semantic connections.
</p>

<h3>17.5 Context mismatch</h3>

<p>
If the target insertion context is incompatible with the snippet content, the IDE MUST reject the import or request user-guided normalization.
Examples include:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>incompatible structure ownership,</li>
  <li>missing required widget context,</li>
  <li>profile-incompatible primitive dependencies,</li>
  <li>unsupported UI libraries.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="validation-rules">18. Validation Rules</h2>

<ul>
  <li>A snippet MUST be structurally valid with respect to its selected ownership scopes.</li>
  <li>A snippet MUST NOT pretend to be a full canonical <code>.frog</code> program unless it independently satisfies the rules of full source, which is outside the base snippet purpose.</li>
  <li>A diagram snippet MUST preserve internal connectivity and represent cut external connections explicitly through boundaries when relevant.</li>
  <li>A front-panel snippet MUST preserve valid widget subtree ownership.</li>
  <li>A paired snippet MUST preserve the intended association between its diagram-side and front-panel-side content.</li>
  <li>Import MUST regenerate identifiers where needed to preserve Program Model uniqueness.</li>
  <li>Import MUST NOT silently create semantic connections not represented by the snippet or explicitly requested by the user.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="illustrative-examples">19. Illustrative Examples</h2>

<h3>19.1 Minimal diagram snippet</h3>

<pre><code>{
  "kind": "frog_snippet",
  "version": "0.1",
  "snippet_kind": "diagram_snippet",
  "diagram_fragment": {
    "nodes": [
      { "id": "n1", "kind": "primitive", "type": "frog.core.add" },
      { "id": "n2", "kind": "primitive", "type": "frog.core.mul" }
    ],
    "edges": [
      {
        "id": "e1",
        "from": { "node": "n1", "port": "result" },
        "to": { "node": "n2", "port": "a" }
      }
    ]
  },
  "boundaries": {
    "inputs": [
      { "node": "n1", "port": "a", "type": "float64" },
      { "node": "n1", "port": "b", "type": "float64" },
      { "node": "n2", "port": "b", "type": "float64" }
    ],
    "outputs": [
      { "node": "n2", "port": "result", "type": "float64" }
    ]
  }
}</code></pre>

<h3>19.2 Front-panel snippet</h3>

<pre><code>{
  "kind": "frog_snippet",
  "version": "0.1",
  "snippet_kind": "front_panel_snippet",
  "front_panel_fragment": {
    "widgets": [
      {
        "id": "temperature_numeric",
        "class": "numeric_indicator",
        "label": "Temperature",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  "preview": {
    "title": "Temperature indicator"
  }
}</code></pre>

<h3>19.3 Paired snippet with widget participation</h3>

<pre><code>{
  "kind": "frog_snippet",
  "version": "0.1",
  "snippet_kind": "paired_snippet",
  "diagram_fragment": {
    "nodes": [
      { "id": "w1", "kind": "widget_value", "widget_id": "gain_knob" },
      { "id": "n1", "kind": "primitive", "type": "frog.core.mul" }
    ],
    "edges": [
      {
        "id": "e1",
        "from": { "node": "w1", "port": "value" },
        "to": { "node": "n1", "port": "a" }
      }
    ]
  },
  "front_panel_fragment": {
    "widgets": [
      {
        "id": "gain_knob",
        "class": "numeric_knob",
        "label": "Gain",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  "boundaries": {
    "inputs": [
      { "node": "n1", "port": "b", "type": "float64" }
    ],
    "outputs": [
      { "node": "n1", "port": "result", "type": "float64" }
    ]
  }
}</code></pre>

