<h2 id="out-of-scope-for-v01">20. Out of Scope for v0.1</h2>

<ul>
  <li>signed snippet packages,</li>
  <li>marketplace distribution metadata,</li>
  <li>full snippet library package management,</li>
  <li>automatic semantic rewrites during import,</li>
  <li>guaranteed cross-profile auto-conversion,</li>
  <li>image-only canonical snippet carriers,</li>
  <li>live executable previews,</li>
  <li>security sandboxing for arbitrary snippet payload execution.</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2 id="summary">21. Summary</h2>

<p>
A FROG Snippet is a reusable IDE artifact for partial program reuse.
It is not the canonical source representation of a full FROG program.
Instead, it captures a structurally valid source-aligned fragment that may later be reinserted into a Program Model.
</p>

<p>
This specification establishes that:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>snippets belong to the IDE layer rather than the canonical full-program source layer,</li>
  <li>the canonical portable standalone snippet extension is <code>.frogsnippet</code>,</li>
  <li>snippets may be diagram-only, front-panel-only, or paired,</li>
  <li>snippets must preserve ownership and structural closure,</li>
  <li>cut external connections are represented explicitly as snippet boundaries,</li>
  <li>import preserves internal fragment meaning while regenerating identifiers as needed,</li>
  <li>preview data is optional and non-authoritative.</li>
</ul>

